Database (Shared)

Both Admin Panel and User Interface use the same tables.

Example:

users
categories
posts
comments

Example relation:

categories
   ↑
posts
   ↑
comments

So:

Admin creates posts

Users read posts

Users add comments

2️⃣ Admin Side (Manage Content)

Admin can:

Create Post
Edit Post
Delete Post
Create Category
Edit Category
Delete Category
Moderate Comments

Example routes:

/admin/posts
/admin/categories
/admin/comments

Example controller:

Admin\PostController
Admin\CategoryController

Example page:

Admin Dashboard
→ Posts
→ Categories
→ Comments

Admin writes content.

3️⃣ User Side (Read Content)

Users only view content.

Example pages:

Home page
Post detail page
Category filter
Archive filter
Comment form

Routes:

/
/post/{id}
/category/{id}
/archive/{month}

Controller:

FrontendController
4️⃣ Example Flow

Admin adds post:

Title: Laravel Blog Tutorial
Category: Laravel
Description: Learn Laravel step by step

Saved in database:

posts table

Now user visits:

http://127.0.0.1:8000

User sees that same post.

5️⃣ Code Example
Admin creates post
Admin\PostController
Post::create([
'title'=>$request->title,
'description'=>$request->description,
'category_id'=>$request->category_id
]);

Saved in:

posts table
User sees post
FrontendController
$posts = Post::with('category')->latest()->get();

Shown in:

site/index.blade.php
6️⃣ Simple Architecture
                DATABASE
           -------------------
           posts | categories
           comments | users
           -------------------

             ↑           ↑
         Admin Panel   User Interface
         (CRUD)        (Read Only)
7️⃣ Why This Is Done

If admin and user used different tables:

admin_posts
user_posts

It becomes very complex and unnecessary.

So CMS systems use same tables.

Examples:

WordPress

Medium

Ghost CMS

All follow this structure.

